    "q1_3": {
      "oversightProcesses": "Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking plans and/or strategies|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking risk management policies|Relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees are informed by management about climate-related issues|Council (or equivalent) is informed by relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees about climate-related issues|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking budgeting and/or major capital expenditures|Climate-related responsibilities are assigned to management-level positions in the government",
      "oversightDetails": "Under the Broads Act 1988, the Broads Authority produces a 5 year management plan, which sets the overarching priorities for the organisation. \\n\\nThe current iteration of the plan (2022-2027) sets Climate Adaptation and Mitigation as the first of 6 themes. This is broken down into A1 - flood and climate risk, A2 - Broads Authority emissions, A3 - wider emissions from the Broads National Park. \\n\\nThe sub-themes are then further broken down into priority actions for 2022-27. \\n\\nThese actions form the basis for the Annual Strategic Priorities and Business Plan, progress against which is reported at each meeting of the Full Authority. \\n\\nAdditionally, as a Protected Landscape the Broads reports through the UK Protected Landscapes Targets and Outcomes Framework, which includes a range of environmental targets which will be annexed to the Broads Plan. \\n\\nThe Authority Members are drawn from elected members of the District and County Councils that overlap the Broads Executive Area, and members appointed by the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs. \\n\\nInternally work on the Climate Change issues is led by a dedicated officer, the Sustainability Manager. They report to a working group consisting of the CEO, the Director of Resources, Director for Delivery, Head of Construction, Maintenance and Ecology, and the Head of Communications \\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n",
      "masterPlanningImpact": "Development Management is carried out in accordance with the Broads Local Plan. The BA is currently preparing a new Local Plan to cover the future development of the Broads, replacing the existing local plan that was adopted in 2019. \\n\\nThe new draft will move into the examination stage in 2026, ahead of being adopted. \\n\\nThe draft local plan includes polices on; \\n\\n- Energy use \\n- Climate adaptation\\n- Flooding \\n- Renewable energy \\n- Transport \\n- Soils protection (of particular relevance in the Broads, given extensive peatland areas) \\n- Sustainable Tourism. \\n\\nFor new buildings, the draft plan has a \\'passivhaus preferred\\' policy, and also asks developers to consider the embodied carbon of buildings, including a presumption against demolition to reduce material use. \\n\\nThe tourism economy is a vital part of the Broads, generating significant local employment and income. The sustainable tourism policy encourages the siting of tourist attractions within reach of public transport to reduce the footprint of travel to the Broads. \\n\\nFor adaptation, the policy requires developments to consider the risks posed by climate change in the future, including sea levels, increased rainfall intensity, and increased periods of extreme heat. ",
      "financialPlanningImpact": "The Broads Authority has secured significant grant funding to support its Nature for Climate programme, through which it is showcasing approaches to restoring peatlands to fight climate change. \\n\\nIt has also received funding to trial a solar powered e-bike charging project, which will support low carbon transport in the Broads.\\n\\nIn 2024/25 it received funding from Active Travel England to develop a Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plan (LCWIP). In 2025/26 it is anticipating receiving revenue support through Active Travel England \\n\\nThe Broads Authority has increased capital expenditure allowances for vehicle replacement to ensure there is adequate budget for electric versions. In the longer term this may be offset by lower running costs. \\n\\nThe authority has also allocated funds for the installation of solar panels on buildings that it owns. \\n\\nHowever at the moment the statutory requirements of the authority and cuts to central government grants means the Authority has limited amounts of its own resources it can commit to climate mitigation. ",
      "transitionRisks": "The primary climate risk in the Broads is from sea level rise and increased incidence of tidal surges. This arises from the low lying nature of the rivers, and the lack of any barrier between the rivers and the sea. \\n\\nIn addition to the flood risk, the tidal surges bring saline incursions that can damage the freshwater wetland ecosystems in the Broads. Many of the rare species in the Broads such as the Swallowtail butterfly, that are major tourism draws, are unable to tolerate salt water. These salt water incursions can also trigger fish deaths which damages the local angling industry. \\n\\nThe economic risks in the Broads are; \\n\\n- The existing Hireboat industry relies on diesel power, and does not have the funds available to convert the cruiser fleet into electric versions. This puts the industry at risk from the wind-down of the fossil fuelled car industry, which it largely depends on for its supply chain. \\n\\n- Agriculture in the Broads is both a major sources of emissions, but also a potential major source of climate mitigation. Rewetting peatlands offers a powerful way to reduce the Broads Carbon Footprint. Currently farmers lack certainty that agricultural subsidy schemes will allow them to continue to be profitable whilst adopting rewetting schemes. "
    },
    "q1_4": {
      "assessesOpportunities": "Yes, wider opportunities/benefits are assessed for some climate actions",
      "assessmentMethod": "Wider opportunities/benefits are qualitatively assessed|Wider opportunities/benefits are considered at the action planning stage",
      "opportunitiesIdentified": "1. Health - Better insulation for homes, better designed homes to resist heat, active travel programmes and dietary changes increasing vegetable consumption and reducing red meat consumption will all improve the health and well being of residents and visitors. \\n\\n2. Better insulation and more microgeneration will reduce energy bills, increasing the resilience of businesses and easing the pressure on household budgets. \\n\\n3. Transitioning away from fossil fuel powered boats in on our rivers and lakes will improve the sense of being in nature and improve our visitors enjoyment. \\n\\n4. Expanding the areas of wetlands by restoring peatland will increase the biodiversity that is one of our key tourism assets. \\n\\n\\n4. Encouraging visitors to arrive by public transport will reduce the impact on local residents of congestion. The improvements in public transport for the visitor economy will also help those local residents who lack good local transport. \\n\\n5. Encouraging access via active travel such as cycling or wheeling will improve public health by increasing activity levels and reducing air pollution. ",
      "equitableDistribution": null,
      "quantifiesEquity": null,
      "equityEvidence": null
    },
    "q1_5": [
      {
        "climateComponent": "Climate risk and vulnerability assessment",
        "govtLevelsEngaged": "State/Regional-level government|Lower level of government|National-level government",
        "engagementPurpose": "The development of this component is required by the national government (e.g., by law, regulation and/or agreement)",
        "comment": "Flood risk within the Broads is the responsibility of the Environment Agency. The assessment of this risk is currently being undertaken in a partnership called the \\'Broadland Futures Initiative\\', which includes the Environment Agency, Natural England, The Drainage Boards, the National Farmers Union and the County Councils. \\n\\nIn the next 12 months this will move to consulting on the future pathways for flood resilience in the Broads. "
      }
    ],
