        "primaryEntity": "Civil society: Academia",
        "mechanisms": "Collaborative initiative|Project implementation and management|Policy and regulation development/ implementation|Knowledge or data sharing",
        "focusAreas": "Education|Natural environment|Resilience|Transport (Mobility)|Waste|Energy|Public health|Inclusive climate action and/or equity|Food|Adaptation",
        "description": "\\'An Inclusive Transition to Net Zero\\'\\n\\nPhase 1. Understand the Challenge. Through training and support from University of York Policy Hub, a group of community researchers from underrepresented neighbourhoods in Bradford which have existing, known obstacles to net zero (e.g. high levels of fuel poverty, low-income areas) were identified to support this climate-related community research project. \\n\\nThe research project started in January 2025 and will complete by December 2025.\\n\\nThe community researcher cohort will feed into the Council's Climate Action Plan and delivery process. The aims of the community-led research include:\\n1.\\tbuilding local residents' skills, readiness, knowledge and awareness to participate in net zero discussions and advocate for change;\\n2.\\tdelivering a series of community-based workshops to understand (evidence) the risks, opportunities and inequalities that different families and communities might face as a result of the transition to net zero; \\n3.\\tco-producing evidence and areas of action to inform the district's Climate Action planning and delivery process, and future applications for climate-related funding.\\n\\nThe community workshops were co-produced with the community researcher cohort in Bradford to assist the full workshop process, including co-design of workshop materials, co-facilitation and contribute to analysis. This included participant recruitment - 16 participants in each location.\\n\\nAs part of the research, facilitation and data management training for community researchers, the University of York Policy Hub team took time to upskill the community and facilitate their long-term support capabilities in the climate change space. This included 'Climate Fresk' training which provided a beginner's overview of climate change science, and made relevant to the communities involved.\\n\\nPhase 2. A three-part in-person workshop series were conducted in the selected neighbourhoods in Bradford during July 2025 - based around \\'Understanding family and community vulnerabilities in transition to Net Zero\\'.\\n\\nWorkshop 1 focused on gaining a common understanding of net zero as a group, learning existing feelings, anxieties and climate change concerns as well as mapping community assets in their neighbourhood and Bradford generally. \\n\\nWorkshop 2 focused on transitioning understanding of their community and their family into a context of net zero. \\n\\nWorkshop 3 focused on Bradford's District Plan, feeding back with suggestions around personal and city level engagement and implementation for best results. This will include aspects of data for community level decision making and data visualisation for communities.\\n\\nPhase 3 & 4 will take place from August - December 20205.\\n\\nPhase 3. Build a vision for Just Climate Futures in the community.\\nUniversity of York will bring together Bradford Council, community and relevant stakeholders in a workshop to build towards action on net zero in Bradford. The aim is to increase community trust and meaningful engagement on the Net Zero District Plan and foster collaborations that may extend beyond the duration of the research project. \\n\\nThe theme of the workshop will be influenced on the outcomes of Phase 1 and 2. involving the community researchers and include activities such as problem solving of a relevant issue (e.g. transportation), creative co-production visuals, community asset and stakeholder mapping, zine-making, and creating principles for implementing the climate action plan based on optimising public benefit.\\n\\nParticipants will include groups/stakeholders not involved in the Climate Action Plan development - and include policy actors, local charity organisations, NGOs, faith leaders, council staff, NHS workers, teachers, employers the council procures work from, and local business owners. These groups do not need to be already involved in the climate change and net zero space.\\n\\nPhase 4. Plan for Just Climate Futures in the Community (Policy and Design for Inclusion).\\n\\nThis involves analysis, outputs and dissemination. The community researchers will be asked if/how they would like to take part in this analysis phase, learning research skills and learning about the analysis process. Outputs will include manifestos, co-produced animation, co-produced policy brief, data visualisation, co-produced full report highlighting the project's process and findings, academic journal articles. \\n\\nA follow-up to this is a half-day worshop entitled 'Inclusive Retrofit: Sharing Solutions Workshop' . This will be delivered by University of Yorkshire in collaboration with WYCA and Bradford Council, hosted in Bradford in November 2025 and bring together policymakers, community groups, and regional actors to develop practical solutions for a fair and and inclusive approach to retrofitting buildings across Yorkshire.\\n\\n\\n\\n",
