        "focusAreas": "Emissions reduction|Finance|Adaptation|Public health|Inclusive climate action and/or equity|Resilience",
        "description": "https://www.bradford.gov.uk/breathe-better-bradford/breathe-better-bradford/\\n\\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0013935125002397\\n\\nFollowing being mandated to implement a Class C Charging Clean Air Zone (CAZ) in 2020, Bradford MDC have collaborated extensively to comply with the direction and the Air Quality (England) Regulations 2010, whilst also improving health and addressing the climate emergency. Following securing the largest funding allocation in the UK for a zone of its type the CAZ was launched using in-house resources, on time and within budget on the 26th September 2022.\\nThe Council have collaborated with Governments Joint Air Quality Unit, the Central Service at the DVLA local businesses and the public to implement the zone, also with the NHS to evaluate health improvements as a result of the CAZ. \\nHealth improvements from significant reductions in Nitrogen Dioxide and reductions in health inequalities (Ref NHS research - Impact of an urban city-wide Bradford clean air plan on health service use and nitrogen dioxide 24 months after implementation: An interrupted time series analysis - ScienceDirect ) saving over \u00a330,000 month in the NHS. These being 24% and 25% reductions in cardiovascular and respiratory GP appointments following the launch of the CAZ.\\n \\n\u00b7 Carbon reduction of 150,000 tons reduction (CO2eq), across the lifetime of the CAZ\\n \\n\u00b7 Fleet transformation to cleanest taxi fleet in the UK with mainly petrol hybrid plus 800 electric vehicles, supported by Council grant scheme.\\n \\nThe CAZ has created a legally ringfenced revenue stream for Bradford MDC to develop a Sustainability Service, a team to deliver emission reduction projects, some of which will lever in private investment for clean growth in the City, examples of projects already underway are: \\n\\nBradford Low Carbon Hydrogen Programme, the largest production and refuelling facility in the UK - a public/private partnership on Council land facilitated by the Councils chairing of the implementation board. 24MW of green Hydrogen. \u00a30.5Bn from Government and \u00a360m private investment (Home - Bradfordhydrogen)\\n \\nLocal Industrial Decarbonisation Project, decarbonising manufacturing. A Council led \u00a31.1m IUK funded project resulting in Bradford Manufacturing Futures (Home | Bradford Cluster) Through collaborative innovation, as a not-for-profit organisation, Bradford Manufacturing Futures aims to champion manufacturers, facilitate the transition to net zero carbon by 2038 and support the sector's growth ambitions. A \u00a3700m programme of joint venture/capital investment to decarbonise the 1,200 manufacturing businesses employing 24,000 people and contributing \u00a31.5billion to the local economy.\\n \\nDistrict Heat Network, 30 major buildings in the City Centre, a \u00a375m project utilising \u00a320m of Green heat network funding. The Council have provided \u00a3273k of funding to lever in additional private and public investment. City Hall will be the first Grade I listed building in the UK to join a heat network.\\n \\nThe Sustainability Service has also supported the development of a Clean Air Schools Programme with \u00a3500k grants for schools, e-bike scheme, a Climate Action Plan for the District, further health research, electric truck trials with local businesses and many other clean growth projects.\\n \\n The Sustainability Service collaborates with public and private partners to add value to the programme; reducing emissions, meeting the air quality objectives, improving health, providing green jobs, fuel security and prosperity for Bradford.\\n",
