    "q1_3": {
      "oversightProcesses": "Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking plans and/or strategies|Council (or equivalent) is informed by relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees about climate-related issues|Climate-related responsibilities are assigned to management-level positions in the government|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when setting performance objectives|Relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees are informed by management about climate-related issues",
      "oversightDetails": "A major procurement exercise undertaken to select a corporate energy partner to form a (15 to 25yr) Joint Venture Partnership to identify and invest in the development of a zero carbon energy infrastructure for the City with an estimated value exceeding \u00a32bn. The successful Joint Venture Partner selected was Eon and a its initial 5yr Plan was approved recently. ",
      "masterPlanningImpact": "The City Council has approved a significant review of the Local Plan in order to strengthen its policies with regards to zero carbon energy efficiency and renewables with allocation of land for solar farms, heat network installations and the specification for energy efficiency standards and insulation levels. The revisions in the local Plan will also address issues regarding adaptation and resilience including the introduction of green spaces for cooling, SUDS for addressing flood risk and to assist water conservation as well as strengtherned policies to promote Biodiversity. The final Plan is currently at the final consultation phase prior to submission to the Planning Inspector on behalf of the Secretary of State for final approval. ",
      "financialPlanningImpact": "Funding was set aside for the establishment of the Strategic Energy Partnership and a series of Gateways established to assess whether the City invests in new proposals put forward to the joint partnersship. Payback returns are calculated to secure investment as well as applications for Government funding for domestic retrofit, roof top solar, school energy projects etc etc. Applications are also made to the Government Investment Back for low energy projects in fact Coventry secured the first Government allocation for funding to a major energy infrastructure at Coventry College and Sydney Stringer Academy School. ",
      "transitionRisks": "A potential risk of moving towards a zero carbon economy is that people working for the traditional carbon based businesses ( e.g. gas fitters and car mechanics etc) could be significantly disadvantaged by the shift to renewables such as solar and new technologies such as heat pumps etc or that the increased costs of green energy impact upon the budgets of low income households.\\n\\nThe City Council and its 25 member organisations on the independent Climate Change Board have signed up to a set of principles to ensure a just transition so that people are supported in their journey from a carbon based to a net zero economy with grants and funding for households on low incomes to retrofit their homes and a Green Skills plan to support companies which may be adversely affected by the changes to a net zero economy. \\n\\nthe Development of a Green Skills Roadmap aims to address access to training for example Coventry College now run boot camps for retrofit and EV car repair."
    },
    "q1_4": {
      "assessesOpportunities": "Yes, wider opportunities/benefits are assessed for many climate actions",
      "assessmentMethod": "Wider opportunities/benefits are qualitatively assessed|Wider opportunities/benefits are considered at the action planning stage|Wider opportunities/benefits are quantitatively assessed",
      "opportunitiesIdentified": "Any actions which address any one or more of the 5 ICLEI Pathway activities are brought into consideration i.e. 1.Carbon Reduction, 2.Circular Economy and waste minimisation, 3.enhancement of Biodiversity, 4.adaptation & resilience and 5. ensuring intragenerational and intergenerational equity (enabling a Just transition). The City Council has a Social and Sustainability Policy https://www.coventry.gov.uk/strategies-plans-policies/social-value-1/4 so when considering recommendations in reports to Cabinet, or receiving planning applications or assessing tenders for procurement of goods and services applies it assess the social and sustainability impact using environmental assessments and the Government's TOMS Framework. https://www.socialvalueportal.com/measurement",
      "equitableDistribution": "Yes, the jurisdiction is collecting disaggregated or spatial data to inform the design and/or monitor the implementation of climate actions",
      "quantifiesEquity": "Priority for investment is based upon detailed socio demographic analysis of geographical areas notably neighbourhoods across the City and where there are opportunities for employment of local residents particularly living within disadvantaged areas. ",
      "equityEvidence": "See the City's latest Climate Change Strategy which details the actions with a whole section devoted to an equitable just transition https://www.coventry.gov.uk/climate-change/climate-change-strategy/9\\n"
    },
