        "mechanisms": "Multi-jurisdictional regional collaboratives|Capacity development|Project implementation and management|Knowledge or data sharing|Development of local/regional adaptation plans, National Adaptation Plans and/or National Adaptation Programmes of Action (NAPAs)|Collaborative initiative",
        "focusAreas": "Inclusive climate action and/or equity|Building and Infrastructure|Resilience|Adaptation|Water|Natural environment|Agriculture",
        "description": "One of Dundee's examples of cross-sector collaboration is Climate Ready Tayside (CRT), a regional adaptation partnership formally launched in September 2025. CRT is a collaboration of government, business, academia, and civil society aiming to prepare the region for the impacts of climate change. CRT's Vision and Priorities were co-developed with over 60 people from 34 local organisations and community groups in Tayside.\\n\\nThe partnership covers the full local authority areas of Angus, Dundee, and Perth & Kinross and is supported by Adaptation Scotland, a programme funded by the Scottish Government. Dundee City Council plays an active role in its governance and delivery, contributing time, staff expertise, and resources to help build the partnership's foundations, including its vision, priorities, governance structure, and branding.\\n\\nThe CRT Vision and Priorities were co-developed through workshops and consultations with over 60 representatives from local organisations and community groups. This inclusive process has built shared ownership of eight regional priorities, spanning themes such as nature-based solutions, health and community resilience, and communication and engagement.\\n\\nConcrete outcomes to date include securing funding for a two-year secretariat role, establishing working groups to drive delivery, and beginning development of a pipeline of priority projects for investment. CRT has also committed in the next two year to host knowledge-sharing events and provide free climate resilience training to local organisations and communities, supporting capacity-building across sectors.\\n\\nBy engaging local authorities, national government programmes, businesses, and civil society in a single coordinated structure, Climate Ready Tayside represents a transformative model of regional collaboration that strengthens local resilience while aligning with the Scottish Government's national adaptation objectives.\\n",
