        "comment": " \u2022Nationally:-Essex County Council (ECC) makes representations on the climate agenda to central government including working with our local MPs to lobby on climate related issues and representing local government at committee hearings in Parliament.-ECC is an 'ally' member of UK100: a network of local leaders who have pledged to lead a rapid transition to net zero with clean air in their communities, ahead of the government's legal target. Cllr Peter Schwier is on a teaching panel for the Climate Leadership Academy 2025 run by UK100. ECC is also part of their Countryside Climate Network-ECC sits on both the Environment Board and the Climate Board of ADEPT, the Association of Directors of Environment, Economy, Planning and Transport. ADEPT brings together directors from county, unitary, metropolitan and combined authorities, along with local enterprise partnerships, sub-national transport bodies and corporate partners drawn from key service sectors. ADEPT members look after roads and transport, environment, local economy and wellbeing, alongside future plans for local areas. The Board aims to share knowledge and understanding of strategic issues and policies relating to climate change and the environment and to develop collaborative responses where needed. The Board advocates that environmental matters - and tackling and adapting to climate change - must be at the heart of decision making.\\n\\n\u2022Regionally:-the East of England Local Government Association's Regional Climate Change Forum - now called Climate East - which Cllr Peter Schwier continues to chair: this group brings together local authorities from across the East of England to share information and approaches to climate action and to amplify action taken by individual authorities. ECC has helped to shape the group's overall direction and is active in workstreams on funding and resourcing, as well as climate adaptation. ECC helped shape the most recent cross-region Climate East conference on resilience including leading workshops on nature-based solutions to reduce flood risk and also developed a logo and identity for the Forum \\n- ECC works closely with District Authorities on climate action and district authorities are represented on the Essex Climate Action Commission.\\n-ECC also works closely with Parish Councils through the Essex Association of Local Councils (EALC). ECC ran a series of climate action forums and events to inform and support Parish Councils, and set up a \u00a30.5m climate action challenge fund which parishes and community groups could apply to for funding to deliver climate action projects. The Essex Climate Action Commission has been involved in the Local Climate Engagement Programme since 2022, supporting towns and parishes to develop local nature plans (https://www.essexclimate.org.uk/local-climate-engagement-programme). \\n- ECC also supports the Rural Community Council of Essex (RCCE) with bespoke webinars and attendance at its events."
