        "mechanisms": "Multi-jurisdictional regional collaboratives|Knowledge or data sharing|Collaborative initiative|Capacity development|Climate action plan implementation",
        "focusAreas": "Forestry|Natural environment|Ecosystem restoration|Agriculture",
        "description": "ECC is one of 48 responsible authorities in England tasked with producing a Local Nature Recovery Strategy (LNRS). The Essex Local Nature Recovery Strategy was published on 10th July 2025 and is one of the first to be published in England. Local Nature Recovery Strategies (LNRSs) are designed to: \\n- deliver the necessary action to reverse the current path of decline in our biodiversity \\n- bring about a recovery for nature \\n\\nThe primary purpose of Essex's LNRS is to find locations for the creation of habitat. It aims to identify the locations most likely to provide the greatest benefit for nature and the wider environment. \\n\\nThe Essex LNRS was produced in collaboration with the Essex Local Nature Partnership and a wide range of key local stakeholders, including: \\n-farmers and landowners \\n-environmental and community groups \\n-parish and town councils \\n-supporting authorities \\n\\nThe Essex LNRS sets out Essex's top 10 Aims for Nature Recovery in the county, including the following: \\n- To create networks of bigger, better, more connected habitats\\n- To have green and blue habitats covering 25% of the county \\nby 2030, with an ambition to achieve 30%, compared to 14% \\ncoverage today\\n(https://essexnaturepartnership.com/essex-lnrs-published/)\\n\\n\\n",
