        "primaryEntity": "Business: Other: community energy membership organisation",
        "mechanisms": "Capacity development|Knowledge or data sharing|Collaborative initiative|Technical assistance",
        "focusAreas": "Emissions reduction|Resilience|Energy",
        "description": "The Community Energy Team within Essex County Council's Energy and Low Carbon Team has made significant strides in supporting and growing the community energy movement across the county.\\n\\nThrough our flagship Pathways programme, we continue to mentor and empower a growing network of community energy groups. What began with just four incorporated groups in 2024 has now doubled to eight, with a further 20 groups actively developing new community-led energy projects. This growth reflects the increasing appetite across Essex for local, sustainable energy solutions.\\n\\nIn July 2025, we are proud to launch the wider rollout of our pioneering Community-Led Energy Planning initiative. Following a successful pilot, this place-based approach is now being introduced in towns and villages across Essex. It enables residents to shape how their local energy systems should evolve, helping communities to co-create tailored strategies for a more sustainable and resilient energy future.\\n\\nWe are also holding renewable energy developers to account, ensuring they contribute meaningfully to the communities they operate in\u2014whether through community benefit funds, shared ownership models, or both. This will ensure that the transition to low-carbon energy is not only green but fair. We are in discussions with over 6 developers with a potential community benefit fund yield of \u00a31.5 million/year for communities across the county. \\n\\nOur monthly Essex Community Energy Network meetings bring together groups from across the county to share knowledge, collaborate, and build a strong community of practice. These sessions foster peer learning and keep the momentum going.\\n\\nWe are also working to strengthen the relationship between schools and community energy groups. By staying on top of policy developments and raising awareness among headteachers and estate managers, we're helping schools become active participants in the local energy transition.\\n\\nInternally, we continue to raise the profile of community energy within Essex County Council, ensuring it is embedded in wider strategic thinking and delivery.\\n\\n",
