        "focusAreas": "Water|Transport (Mobility)|Education|Industry|Landscape and jurisdictional approaches|Energy|Building and Infrastructure",
        "description": "The new National Energy System Operator (NESO), has been commissioned by the Department for Energy Security and Net Zero (DESNZ) to provide independent advice on the pathways towards the 2030 Clean Power ambition. NESO will also produce a Regional Energy Strategic Plan (RESP) to bring together local and regional stakeholders to create joined-up energy plans (including electricity, gas, and hydrogen) for each region of Great Britain. There will be a RESP for the Eastern region covering Essex, Suffolk and Norfolk. The RESP aims to support local strategic priorities as well as national goals related to clean power. It does this by informing Ofgem's 5-yearly Electricity Price Control (ED) determination with the network operator (which in Essex is UK Power Networks). The next ED period is ED3 which covers 2028-2033. ED3 will be determined in early 2026 and NESO will provide a 'Transitional Regional Energy Strategic Plan' (tRESP) to support the outcome. This is in advance of NESO developing a more \u201cenduring RESP\u201d in late-2027 to a pathway to 2050. The tRESP serves as an opportunity for ECC to feed in its priorities for growth and identify areas of strategic network investment need. ECC are currently inputting data on strategically important projects to inform the tRESP. ECC have convened a working group that covers multiple internal and external partners to input projects from across Essex. ECC will be engaging fully with the RESP process and have already attended multiple forum meetings and responded to consultations and will continue to do so as the work progresses.",
