        "description": "\u2022 Glasgow City Council is a member of various working groups established by the Scottish Government to develop regulatory frameworks relating to heat decarbonisation and the delivery of local authorities Local Heat and Energy Efficiency Strategies (LHEES).\\n\u2022 Sustainable Scotland Network (SSN) is a Scottish public sector network on sustainability and climate change (https://sustainablescotlandnetwork.org/about-us/steering-group). SSN supports member organisations but also provides local authorities the opportunity to contribute towards upcoming changes in legislation and guidance on climate action.\\n\u2022 On behalf of Glasgow City Region, the council-led Clyde Metro Team is supporting the development of Clyde Metro's Case For Investment. The Scottish Government confirmed Clyde Metro as a key future mass transit transport investment priority, bringing together Strathclyde Partnership for Transport (SPT) as programme lead, Glasgow City Council for Glasgow City Region, and Transport Scotland to look at a long-term integrated approach to transport infrastructure and services across the region. It will also look at corridor master planning to enable Clyde Metro's reach to extend beyond the value of improved connectivity to deliver wider transformation benefits to sustainability, environment, housing, placemaking, economy, health, and social strategies. (https://citizen.glascc1-prd.gosshosted.com/article/2558/Clyde-Metro) \u2022 GCC is a member of The Cities Climate Finance Leadership Alliance (CCFLA) is a coalition of leaders committed to deploying finance for city level climate action at scale by 2030 (https://citiesclimatefinance.org/about/city-ambassadors). By being a part of CCFLA and by contributing expertise access to networks and funding leaders have committed to work together to bridge supply and demand for sustainable climate-friendly and resilient development at the sub-national level.\\n\u2022 GCC has worked with and learnt from its urban peers through the Core Cities and London Boroughs network to through the UK Cities Commission for Climate Investment (now called 3Ci) (https://www.3ci.org.uk/about/). It is specifically aimed at driving additional investment into local net zero programmes and supporting cities to bring forward a pipeline of projects to government and the private capital markets. This has helped to add further prominence and greater potential opportunities to Glasgow's own green investment prospectus and ensured that a meaningful legacy relationship with other cities across the UK has been taken forward from COP26. (https://invest-glasgow.foleon.com/igpubs/glasgow-greenprint-for-investment/table-of-contents)",
