        "description": "Future Neighbourhoods 2030 collaborates with Local Authorities and other relevant organisations through a Future Neighbourhoods Forum. We are collaborating with Somers Town, in the London Borough of Camden, and Notting Dale, in the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea, to support their implementation of GLA grant funded projects. We are also working with a consultant to learn from the experience of the Future Neighbourhoods in an evaluation piece of work, this has included workshopping with the Future Neighbourhoods. We have collaborated with the Mayoral Design Advocates and the Future Neighbourhoods to produce Future Neighbourhood strategies. We are currently working with a consultant to provide technical support on how Future Neighbourhoods 2030 can fund and finance projects. We have also worked with a consultant to produce KPIs for the Future Neighbourhoods 2030. \\n\\nWarmer Homes London (WHL) is a collaborative retrofit hub jointly established by the Mayor of London and London Councils, partnering with boroughs, housing associations, builders, and community energy groups to enhance energy efficiency across the capital's housing stock. WHL centralises funding and strategy to streamline retrofit delivery, replacing fragmented borough-by-borough approaches and provides a \\'one-London approach\\', improving access to long-term funding and strengthening supply chains. It has secured \u00a3231m from central government to upgrade approximately 22,000 homes, made up of \u00a3175m from the Warm Homes Social Housing Fund and \u00a356 million via the Warm Homes Local Grant (WHLG) for low-income private households across 31 boroughs. Alongside this, boroughs and housing associations have pledged over \u00a3100 million in additional match funding for social housing retrofit. The Mayor's direct contribution is almost \u00a310 million over four years to support the WHL delivery vehicle, with \u00a3400,000 in startup support from boroughs.\\n\\nThe London Surface Water Strategy has been developed with collaboration at its heart, bringing together partners including Local Authorities, Environment Agency, Thames Water and TfL across London to deliver London's first surface water strategy published in 2025. We are currently working on implementation of the strategy focusing on delivery of SuDS by enabling further collaboration between partners to scale up delivery. This includes producing a model to distribute funding from partners, setting up collaboration agreements to enable taking forward the surface water catchment action plan.\\n",
