        "mechanisms": "Capacity development|Project delivery - Public Private Partnership|Collaborative initiative|Procurement|Financing (investment)|Knowledge or data sharing|Project implementation and management|Cleaner production industry support|Funding (grants)|Reporting of climate and/or environmental data|Circular economy business model support|Economic development",
        "focusAreas": "Building and Infrastructure|Resilience|Public health|Water|Food|Waste|Energy|Natural environment|Adaptation|Emissions reduction",
        "description": "One of the most significant examples of collaboration in Greater Manchester is the Mission Based Approach which brings together over 200 individuals from over 100 organisations to collaborate on the actions outlined in the Five Year Environment Plan. When setting out the targets in the Five Year Environment Plan it was acknowledged that the ambitious targets could not be completed by GMCA alone but required everyone in GM to get involved. The Mission Based Approach developed by University College London Institute for Innovation for Public Purpose takes an ambitious goal such as 'carbon neutrality by 2038' and breaks it down into manageable goals and identifies the sectors that need to be involved. Under the Mission Based Approach GMCA has set up five Challenge Groups to address the specific actions under their theme in the Five Year Environment Plan. - Communications and Behaviour Change - Low Carbon - Natural Environment- Sustainable Consumption and Production The groups meet up every quarter with a focus on action and delivery and are chaired by organisations external to GMCA, these chairs then sit on the Green City Region Partnership and report on progress. In between the meetings several task and finish groups meet, these are smaller groups which focus on a smaller task e.g. delivering a policy report, project delivery, research etc. There is also a 5YEP Forum group which acts as a challenge and support to the other groups as well as disseminating information about key climate action to a wide audience. A more detailed overview of Greater Manchester's Mission Based Approach can be viewed on this blog by UCL IIPP https://medium.com/iipp-blog/mission-oriented-approaches-in-practice-greater-manchesters-2038-carbon-neutral-challenge-a28e3d00cbc",
