    "q1_3": {
      "oversightProcesses": "Council (or equivalent) is informed by relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees about climate-related issues|Relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees are informed by management about climate-related issues|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking plans and/or strategies|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking risk management policies",
      "oversightDetails": "n/a",
      "masterPlanningImpact": "The new National Park Partnership Plan (2024-29) was approved by the Board in December 2023 and by the Minister in 2024. It commits to becoming a net zero National Park by 2035. https://www.lochlomond-trossachs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/NPPP-2024_RGB.pdf\\n \\nAction on climate change is embedded throughout the Plan's outcomes, objectives, actions and measures of success, and the Plan's overarching vision is a thriving place that is nature positive and carbon negative. \\n\\nThe National Park Partnership Plan \\nguides how all of those with a role to \\nplay in looking after the National Park \\nwill work together to manage the Park \\nand achieve a shared vision for the area. \\n\\nA National Park Plan is required under \\nthe National Parks (Scotland) Act 2000 \\nto set out a National Park Authority's \\npolicy for (a) managing a National Park; \\nand (b) coordinating the exercise of an \\nAuthority's functions in relation to a \\nNational Park and the functions of other \\npublic bodies and office holders to the \\nextent that they affect a National Park, \\nwith a view to ensuring that the National \\nPark aims are collectively achieved in a \\nco-ordinated way.",
      "financialPlanningImpact": "With significant climate action being central to our National Park Partnership Plan, staff time and resources are being prioritised for it's delivery. Key corporate processes (such as annual setting of the organisation's budget, resource allocation for projects, and financial reporting) must reflect delivery against the Partnership Plan objectives.\\n\\n",
      "transitionRisks": "Overall, there will need to be a significant growth in nature-based jobs (and associated skills development and business development) in sectors central to the transition - such as peatland restoration, woodland creation and management, public transport provision, and nature-based tourism.\\n\\nManaging land use for carbon storage, public water supply and flood management will become more important but more difficult. The National Park Partnership Plan supports the rapid transition to a low carbon economy for land-based sectors, ensuring that land use change delivers sustainable land management, and improvements to soils/increased carbon sequestration. As well as demonstrating how nature-based solutions can help develop resilience to climate change at a landscape scale. But this is not an easy transition for the land management sector, and support will be needed at national, regional and local scales in order for it to be made. There is also arguably a lack of integration of policy drivers and subsidy schemes at a national level which is impacting the pace and scale of change needed. \\n\\nLong-standing rural car dependency (for residents and visitors) is a significant impediment to emission reduction and quality of life, which is difficult to effectively tackle. It requires a new and ambitious multi-agency, long-term and 'whole-system' approach which we have laid out in our National Park Partnership Plan. If buy-in and delivery by the relevant partners cannot be secured or sustained over the longer-term this is a key risk to the transition.\\n\\nThe tourism sector is experiencing very difficult operating circumstances with escalating operating costs, skills shortages, changing markets and recruitment challenges. This presents a risk to the rapid decarbonisation and pivoting to new markets required by the transition.\\n\\nTransition from fossil fuel heating systems in homes, particularly in rural areas, is also a key area currently at risk at a national level.\\n"
    },
    "q1_4": {
      "assessesOpportunities": "Yes, wider opportunities/benefits are assessed for some climate actions",
      "assessmentMethod": "Wider opportunities/benefits are considered at the post-implementation monitoring and evaluation stage|Wider opportunities/benefits are considered at the action planning stage|Wider opportunities/benefits are considered at the action implementation stage",
      "opportunitiesIdentified": "As part of developing the Partnership plan 2024-29 we looked at the integration of climate action with other policy objectives (particularly nature restoration and quality of life for residents and visitors of the National Park) and how we can maximise co-benefits. For example, afforestation and peatland restoration done in the right way and in the right places will deliver for biodiversity, climate action and growth of the peatland and woodland sectors (and associated economic activity). Similarly, reduction in rural car dependency is essential to reach net zero, as well as to improve access to rural services and amenities, and requires significant growth in the sector(s) providing public transportation. Individual projects and programmes of work underway in the National Park also look at the development and delivery of co-benefits.\\n\\nA dedicated climate action plan for the National Park will be developed over the next year which can more systematically look at the wider benefits of the climate actions within it.",
      "equitableDistribution": "Do not know",
      "quantifiesEquity": null,
      "equityEvidence": "n/a\\n"
    },
