        "focusAreas": "Emissions reduction|Building and Infrastructure|Energy",
        "description": "In July 2021, Energy Saving Trust (EST) was commissioned by the North of Tyne Combined Authority (now North East Combined Authority) to develop a robust evidence base to inform the business case for a large scale housing retrofit programme. EST investigated two main retrofit scenarios. The Business as Usual (BAU) scenario assumed a continuation of historical trends in retrofit funding and delivery in the North of Tyne. The Net Zero scenario assumed extensive energy efficiency and lower carbon heating system upgrades with the goal of achieving net zero emissions. In order to achieve net zero, local retrofit rates across the NTCA will need to ramp up quickly. The Net Zero scenario will require over 80,000 homes to be retrofitted per year by 2027: more than 10 times the current rate. Additionally, the cost of achieving the Net Zero scenario will require an estimated 13bn in funding for the tri-borough area, beyond BAU funding sources (eg current and forthcoming grant funding). This has led to the creation of a one-stop-shop for retrofit across the three local authorities to achieve net-zero emissions across the housing stock. The EST report estimates that to achieve net-zero emissions in North Tyneside this will require the average home to attain a SAP score of 86 (EPC B), which will generate annual kWh savings of 1.4billion kWh across all homes and annual bill savings of 51million, taking the carbon footprint of the housing stock from 477,000tonnesCO2e to 44,100tCO2e - an emissions reduction of 91% against a 2021 emissions baseline. This entails retrofitting the average home with 7.2 energy efficiency measures and is estimated to cost 3.3billion for all homes in the borough. Most of this will need to be funded by homeowners, energy suppliers, and central government funding either directly to householders or channelled through schemes such as the Green Homes Grant/Sustainable Warmth and Social Housing Decarbonisation. Now firmly established, the One-Stop-Shop is the critical enabler to retrofit at scale across all homes, regardless of income, providing end-to-end project management and signposting to appropriately qualified installers, recognised technologies, energy modelling and financing options. Funding will need to be sought to continue the one stop shop beyond the pilot end date of March 2025\\n\\nIn June 2025 approval was given to deliver the North East CA's Retrofit Programme 2025-27 which has been renamed as the North East Warm Homes Service. This comprises three main elements: provision of a new North East Warm Homes one stop shop service; introduction of a low interest retrofit loan to be incorporated into the North East Warm Homes service; and formation of the North East Warm Homes Taskforce to support the development of a regional retrofit strategy and action plan to underpin future retrofit activity. Following the procurement of the North Tyneside Council have supported the CA in the evaluation of the tenders to manage this second phase of retrofit work across the seven North East authority areas. \\n",
        "otherEntities": "Regional government|Neighboring local government|Energy"
