        "focusAreas": "Energy|Building and Infrastructure|Inclusive climate action and/or equity",
        "description": "In partnership with energy company E.ON, North Tyneside council is delivering the UK government's Green Homes Grant which is a scheme that aims to help homeowners and landlords in England cover the cost of certain energy saving home improvements. Residents with a household annual income below 30,000 or if someone in the household is in receipt of a means tested benefit e.g. Universal Credit, and a low energy-efficient property - with a rating of D, E, F or G - were eligible to apply for the full cost of having a range of energy-efficient and low carbon measures installed at home. Under the Local Authority Delivery Scheme 1 (LAD1) and Local Authority Delivery Scheme 2 (LAD2), the council delivered 4.4 million worth of investment, installing over 600 measures to low-income homes, bringing 386 properties to EPC C ratings. North Tyneside Council are in the process of delivering the Local Authority Delivery Scheme 3 (LAD3) of the Green Homes Grant which consists of 320 new home improvement measures worth 3.7 million of investment. 274 new measures have been delivered from LAD3 funding to date. We have now secured \u00a34.281m for domestic energy efficiency measures from the Warm Homes Local Grant. The co-benefits of this will support lower household energy bills and improve health outcomes. All these engagement practices have helped us to install over 2,300 carbon reduction measures across our housing stock in 2024/25 including the installation of Solar PV arrays, cavity wall insulation, loft insulation, internal wall insulation, low energy lighting and high efficiency condensing boilers.\u202f",
