    "q1_3": {
      "oversightProcesses": "Relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees are informed by management about climate-related issues|Council (or equivalent) is informed by relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees about climate-related issues|Climate-related responsibilities are assigned to a committee(s) or a subcommittee(s) in the government|Climate-related responsibilities are assigned to management-level positions in the government|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking risk management policies|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking plans and/or strategies",
      "oversightDetails": "The Peak District National Park Authority (PDNPA) uses a number of internal policies to inform and track oversight of climate related issues. These involve:\\n- The PDNPA Carbon Management Plan 2020-2050: A plan for managing the greenhouse gas emissions from our buildings and \\noperations.\\n- The National Park Management Plan (NPMP) 2023-28: Aim 2 focuses on Climate Change, and sets objects for the Authority and it's partners' work on climate change.\\n- The Climate Change Vulnerability Assessment (CCVA): This accounts for impacts of climate change on the special qualities of the Peak District, and in the next Management Plan cycle will be used to inform adaptation and mitigation planning. \\n\\nThese documents are prepared by National Park Officers with support from constituent authorities and other partners. They are approved by Members of the Authority, with work relating to climate change being reviewed annually (in September) by full Authority meetings.\\n\\nPDNPA Officers are also involved in the National Parks UK Climate Change and Energy Group, which is chaired by PDNPAs CEO, where officers across the UK support each other to maintain oversight of climate related issues.",
      "masterPlanningImpact": "The overarching governing document for the Peak District National Park is the National Park Management Plan, a partnership document which governs the work of the National Park Authority as well as numerous other delivery partners. This has four guiding aims, one of which is dedicated to climate change as a result of and acknowledgement of the significant impact that climate-related issues will have in the National Park. This aim is further detailed in subsequent sections.\\n\\nPDNPA has a statutory responsibility to produce a Local Plan to detail policy which guides development. This is currently being updated, with the new draft plan set to be submitted to the Secretary of State in December 2026. Climate change is a key consideration in the updates to the new draft plan, which sets out policies on sustainable development, development which supports adaptation to climate change, and requirements to meet net zero targets. Work is ongoing which aims to bring this draft more closely in line with the other climate change-related policies (referenced in previous answer).\\n",
      "financialPlanningImpact": "Not yet considered",
      "transitionRisks": "Not yet considered"
    },
    "q1_4": {
      "assessesOpportunities": "Intending to assess wider opportunities/benefits of all climate actions in the next 2 years",
      "assessmentMethod": null,
      "opportunitiesIdentified": null,
      "equitableDistribution": "No, but the jurisdiction is intending to incorporate measures in the next 2 years",
      "quantifiesEquity": null,
      "equityEvidence": "We are about to commence (Oct 2025) the initial stages of consultation and partnership to begin developing the next National Park Management Plan. This is the high level partnership document which governs the overall aims and direction of the National Park, and as such is undertaken in consultation with local communities and visitor groups, as well as delivery partners such as land managers and businesses. Climate change will be a core consideration within this planning process, and as such discussions regarding climate action, its impacts, and benefits will be held with stakeholders, partners and collaborators as part of this process. We will aim to use this understand, and ideally support the resourcing of, those who are delivering on climate action, e.g. by continuing our work to support the development of climate-adaptive and mitigative farming practises through access to subsidies and training. \\n\\nIn addition, we are intending to integrate the Resist-Accept-Direct decision making framework into the next management plan, to increase the ability of those delivering the management plan to respond to and manage change. This will allow a greater depth of understanding and planning for how action related to climate adaptation and mitigation is undertaken, by whom, and under what conditions. "
    },
