        "focusAreas": "Waste|Building and Infrastructure|Industry|Food|Transport (Mobility)|Landscape and jurisdictional approaches|Finance|Forestry|Social Services|Adaptation|Education|Energy|Agriculture|Inclusive climate action and/or equity|Natural environment|Resilience|Emissions reduction|Water|Ecosystem restoration|Public health",
        "description": "In March 2023 Sunderland City Council launched a new Green Champions program for employees. \\nEarly activities included recruitment of interested volunteers at three staff events, where the Council's and city's Low Carbon ambitions, framework and plans have been shared as well as information on specific Low Carbon topics (Active and sustainable transport in May and July 2023 and Reducing Consumption and Waste with links to Refill Sunderland and Plastic free month in July). \\nOther staff have been recruited through participation in the Sunderland 60 Common Purpose Legacy projects (2023, 2024 & 2025), where young Council employees were invited to become Green Champions for their work areas. \\nThe Council's Green Champions network continues to grow. Meetings have included new participants from City Planning, Social Services, Human Resources and Organisational Development, and Regulatory Services among others taking the total number Green Champions to 42 (August 2025). \\nGreen Champions have been consulted on areas where their input is valuable, including the staff induction process for all new starters in which a face-to-face interactive session on Low Carbon and sustainable regeneration is now included monthly. They continue to feedback and support the iLearn online training module which is now available for all Council staff and includes information on both climate science and actions in the workplace/locally. \\nThe Green Champions are also continuing to identify areas where sustainable improvements can be made within their own diverse service areas - these have included postal system reviews, allotment provision and support, uniform swaps, and equipment recycling. Green Champions are also participating in the creation of media content to ensure staff comply with recycling in City Hall and other council workplaces (July 2025). \\n \\nMeetings are held on a quarterly basis (Jan, Apr, July, Oct), and key speakers are invited to discuss an area of interest. Topics discussed this year have included the Links With Nature Project, the role of the Voluntary Community Sector, Active Travel & Transport, and Coast projects. \\nA Network has been created to run concurrently, for tenants of the City Hall Building, led by Knight Frank. The City Hall Green Champions Tenants meetings are a vehicle to share best practice and lead on all things sustainable.\\n\\nIn 2024, Sunderland's City Hall was awarded a prestigious environmental award for its efforts to reduce emissions and embrace sustainable practices. Construction at Riverside Sunderland was awarded the Silver Accreditation by the Investors in the Environment Scheme (iiE), as through to completion, ecological responsibility measures have been proactively put in place to improve the building's environmental impact from the offset.\\n\\nInformation relating to the city's low carbon journey continues to be available for staff to access via a Council digital hub and it is embedded into the Council's induction programme, alongside the roll out of Carbon Literacy Training for senior managers across the Council.",
        "otherEntities": "NGO and associations"
