      "oversightDetails": "The Council has set a Climate Change Strategy that sets ambitions for Surrey to be Net zero and resilient by 2050. Following this the Council has developed Climate Change Delivery Plan that stipulates how targets of the Climate Change Strategy will be met. The Council has set up internal teams led by the Greener Futures team to lead its response to implementing the ambition in the Climate change strategy through coordination internally with all directorates and external partner to manage climate related risks. These risks include physical impacts of Climate Change that monitored by officers in the Council ",
      "masterPlanningImpact": "Surrey County Council has no control over Local Plans and development plan documents produced by each borough and district council. Surrey County Council is responsible for developing a new Joint Minerals and Waste Management Plan which is currently at the start of development and it is intended to consider climate risks, nature recovery and encourage emissions reduction where possible within the parameters set by the National Planning Policy Framework.",
      "financialPlanningImpact": "The Green Finance Strategy, which sets out the principles and approach to funding the Greener Futures Climate Change Delivery Plan 2021-2025, was agreed by Surrey County Council's Cabinet in July 2023 and an annual review of the funding landscape will take place. The Council's Medium Term Financial Strategy to to 2025/26 includes delivering on the Surrey Climate Change Strategy. ",
      "transitionRisks": "There are risks connected to connecting renewable energy to the grid. These include technical risks, such as faults in the project and equipment, delays in construction, inadequate design, and poor workmanship in the installation. There are also legal risks in transitioning to a low-carbon economy. Planning authorities allow oil and gas drilling, and we as a local authority do not have the power to stop these, which damages our reputation. Similarly, we do not have the power to improve the transport infrastructure enough to allow people to use public transport easily and efficiently, which damages our reputation. We do not control the decarbonisation of the national grid, or the expansion of the EV charging network, and as such, we are at risk of not meeting our net-zero targets and having our reputation damaged."
