    "q1_3": {
      "oversightProcesses": "Climate-related responsibilities are assigned to a committee(s) or a subcommittee(s) in the government|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking budgeting and/or major capital expenditures|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking risk management policies|Climate-related responsibilities are assigned to management-level positions in the government|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when setting performance objectives|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking plans and/or strategies|Council (or equivalent) is informed by relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees about climate-related issues",
      "oversightDetails": "The Cabinet, who make decisions on whether projects should proceed, allow initiatives to be funded and give general steer on Council work, are regularly updated by the Climate Change team, either as a regular report (e.g. the Overview and Scrutiny Committee receives a report each January on climate communications) or ad-hoc when projects that require approval come into being (e.g. a project to put solar mats on bin lorries). The Cabinet is frequently asked for funds to support Climate Change projects, and always considers these when deciding how money should be spent within WDC e.g. they considered using Section 106 money to fund a sustainable travel initiative, when projects from other areas could also have used the money. The Climate Change Team has a managerial Team Leader, who has climate responsibilities related to the introduction of EVs and sustainable transport in the District. The Low Cost Low Carbon Programme Board is made up of councillors, including a specific Climate Change Portfolio Holder, and is assigned climate-related tasks when it meets once every six weeks e.g. approving the installation of LED bulbs at a WDC-owned theatre. WDC's plans and strategies mention and consider climate change e.g. the Corporate Strategy mentions it specifically in its own section, and the Risk Management policy mentions it as a source of risk. There is a separate set of performance objectives specific to climate change, which are reviewed each year and assessed to see how effective climate change mitigation activities are.",
      "masterPlanningImpact": "Climate change is considered in every aspect of planning where it is relevant. For instance, WDC's Corporate Strategy has a section dedicated to climate change, which can be seen here: https://www.warwickdc.gov.uk/info/20854/corporate_strategy/1912/corporate_strategy_warwick_district_2030/9 Priority 2 is specifically linked to climate change and sets out WDC's commitment to reducing emissions from public and private buildings in the area in general. The Principles of the Strategy (https://www.warwickdc.gov.uk/info/20854/corporate_strategy/1912/corporate_strategy_warwick_district_2030/4) explain that sustainability is at the heart of every decision WDC makes, and that the safety of the environment is at the heart of our planning and investing.",
      "financialPlanningImpact": "https://www.warwickdc.gov.uk/info/20854/corporate_strategy/1912/corporate_strategy_warwick_district_2030/4 The Corporate Strategy Principles explain how climate change issues are considered whenever an investment is made, particularly long-term investments.",
      "transitionRisks": "Risk 1: Change to Political Priorities: Tension between delivering ambitions set out in Climate Change Action Programme and the Low Cost Low Carbon Strategy created in 2024.\\nRisk 2: Cost of achieving priorities: Several planned priorities are currently unfunded, but are likely to be expensive.\\nRisk 3: Climate change impacting on WDC services: increasing local impacts from climate change and increasing costs of supporting adaptation.\\nRisk 4: Lack of staff resources or expertise to deliver policies: Many aspects of the team's workload require specialist skills. It is also important to ensure sufficient team capacity, given the priority of Climate Change work.\\nRisk 5: National Policy: National Government support, policies and funding are not sufficient to enable achievement of Climate Change work."
    },
