        "comment": "The Mayor of the West Midlands, Richard Parker, has set about establishing strong relationships with key government departments in relation to net zero and the environment. This has been done in a number of ways, including attendance at the Mayoral meeting at 10 Downing Street. The Mayor also wrote a letter to the following people (and more): Ed Miliband MP, Minister for DESNZ. Parker outlined the leading role the WMCA can play in the transition to a greener, more sustainable future and accelerating towards net zero. This includes through retrofit and regional energy planning. Steve Reed MP, Minister for Defra. Parker outlined the importance of the region's biodiversity and natural environment and the role that the WMCA can play in key areas of delivery around nature and climate adaptation (noted that in the latest reshuffle, Steve Reed has left Defra. The Mayor has also met Mary Creagh MP, another Defra minister to discuss climate actions). As well as letters and discussions with senior ministers, the WMCA has also engaged directly with government departments, which has included writing letters to the following people: Jeremy Pocklington, Permanent Secretary, DESNZ. Parker again outlined the role that the WMCA can play in net zero, asking for devolved powers and money to deliver, as well as key legislation change to support the WMCA's ambition. Tamara Finkelstein, Permanent Secretary, Defra. Parker again outlined the role that the WMCA can play in improving the environment and reducing emissions, highlighting the value of devolved power and funding on nature recovery, climate adaptation, air quality and circular economy. The Mayor continues to work with government and other regional mayors to call for further devolution of power and money, beyond the initial Integrated Settlement (April 2025) for the West Midlands to lead on the environment and climate action. \\n"
