        "focusAreas": "Industry|Emissions reduction|Building and Infrastructure|Waste",
        "description": "The WMCA has a circular economy delivery programme which is guided by a circular economy routemap published in 2021. The circular economy routemap aims to encourage materials efficiency in the West Midlands economy through an initial focus on three strategically important areas: manufacturing, construction, and food. The circular economy programme has two main areas which has seen extensive industry collaboration to date, the industrial symbiosis project and subsequent West Midlands Resource Reuse Network, and the delivery of Zero Waste Construction Hubs. Firstly, the West Midlands Resource Reuse Network is a materials focused business support programme currently being piloted directly with businesses in the region. The aim of the Network is to support businesses to become more materials efficient by creating a network of businesses engaging in the mutually beneficial transfer of waste and resources, such that one company's waste becomes another's raw material. Setting up and delivering the Network has required substantial levels of collaboration with the business community in the region. The delivery of the Network is based on a business case that the WMCA completed in 2022, which aimed to co-create the project with the regional business community and industry groups. The second area of circular economy delivery that has required extensive business collaboration is the delivery of the Zero Waste Construction Hubs project. The Zero Waste Construction Hubs project aims to reduce the amount of waste produced by the construction sector by developing the infrastructure required to facilitate materials recovery from active construction sites. The WMCA conducted a feasibility study which engaged heavily with the region's construction sector to assess the feasibility of the concept in the region. Following the confirmation of feasibility, the WMCA convened a community interest company and a local charity to deliver the first pilot hub in Wolverhampton, which successfully opened in July 2024.\\n\\nIn 2026, the WMCA will feature as a headline partner in the delivery of Circular Economy UK 2026, a first of its kind conference that will bring together local, regional, and national, stakeholders from the public and private sectors to identify how collaboration can further support and accelerate the uptake of the circular economy. ",
