        "mechanisms": "Financing (investment)|Collaborative initiative|Cleaner production industry support|Convening industry groups|Economic development",
        "focusAreas": "Energy|Emissions reduction|Transport (Mobility)|Industry",
        "description": "In March 2023, the Government launched an Investment Zone programme across eight Combined Authority areas in England, including the West Midlands. This initiative aims to bolster priority sectors through additional funding, business rates growth retention, and tax incentives to stimulate private sector investment. The WMCA has designated its Investment Zone to support advanced manufacturing, with a focus on Electric Vehicles, Battery Technology, Digital, Green Industries, Sustainable Construction and Healthtech. The WMIZ have been working collaboratively with all local authorities and Universities in the WM region and HMG partners to ensure the programme incorporates multiple aspects of the inclusive growth framework, and wider WMCA and HMG priorities on growth, innovation and green industry including considerations around climate/net zero. Key climate-related elements include the promotion of battery technology crucial for decarbonising homes and businesses, electric vehicles, transitioning to renewable fuel sources and the integration of air quality programmes and natural environment schemes to enhance local environments. Additionally, the WMIZ supply chain transition programme aids businesses in shifting to these new emerging green industries, further supporting the region's net-zero goals. The WMIZ's commitment to green sectors is evident, with two of the three Investment Zone sites being dedicated to developing green industries, engineering, and technology, (Wolverhampton's Green Innovation Corridor and Coventry and Warwick Gigapark) driving forward the green agenda, economic growth, job creation and skill development in these key sectors that would contribute to greater climate security in the future.\\nThe West Midlands Investment Zone seeks to transform our regional economy, creating 30,000 jobs, catalyzing \u00a35.5 billion in private sector investment, with \u00a31.5bn business rate growth retained for reinvestment into sites and wider economic growth across the region. Much of this growth will focus on the low-carbon economy. ",
