      {
        "primaryEntity": "Business: Industry trade group",
        "mechanisms": "Reporting of climate and/or environmental data|Collaborative initiative|City business partnership platform|Requirement to develop and implement emissions reduction target",
        "focusAreas": "Emissions reduction|Building and Infrastructure|Energy",
        "description": "In late 2022 Westminster City Council launched a Sustainable City Charter for businesses and public bodies in Westminster, in partnership with the Westminster Property Association (WPA). The Charter is a public pledge open to any organisation which owns or occupies non-domestic buildings within Westminster's boundaries. By signing up to the Charter, organisations must agree to a series of seven key commitments related to their buildings, including: targeting net zero operational emissions for their buildings by 2040, implementing sustainable procurement policies for their buildings , actively engaging with their landlords and/or tenants to reduce building emissions, reducing waste and transport emissions and creating delivery consolidation schemes. To become a signatory, organisations must complete an application form setting out their specific aims for the year ahead and must report on energy use across their buildings in Westminster each year. In return, Charter signatories get access to exclusive knowledge-sharing events, are promoted in the media, and have first access to a range of council schemes. We are also developing additional benefits for Charter signatories including a digital toolkit for Charter signatories. The charter now has 63 organisations as full signatories, with another 70 in the process of signing up across Westminster, including a number of large landowners and developers such as Landsec, Derwent, Grosvenor Estate and other major institutions such as the Royal Opera House, LSE, University of Westminster and Imperial College NHS Trust. More information about the Charter can be found here: https://www.westminster.gov.uk/tackling-climate-change-westminster/business-climate-action/sustainable-city-charter",
        "otherEntities": "Industrials|NGO and associations|Education sector|Energy"
      }
