    "q1_3": {
      "oversightProcesses": "Council (or equivalent) is informed by relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees about climate-related issues",
      "oversightDetails": "In order to scrutinise and strengthen the Action Plan, a specific Climate Emergency Overview and Scrutiny Management Committee regularly meet to review the emerging targets and key performance indicators underpinning the plan, recommending potential improvements to help make it more robust, transparent and evidence based. The Council used this extensive input as the basis for further work, focused in particular on our approach to enable the engagement of residents and key stakeholders across the Borough, as well as to clarify the impact of specific schemes and ensure that they were supported by SMART targets. Ongoing workstream groups for each section of the action plan ensure internal oversight of the plan, its actions and the progress towards them. The plan itself, and actions within, are then reviewed by senior officers and council members through the full democratic process, to ensure full consultation and oversight.",
      "masterPlanningImpact": "In response to the rising concern over the urgent need for action, in July 2019, Wokingham Borough Council members unanimously declared a climate emergency. The declaration set out the commitment to play as full a role as possible, leading by example as well as by exhortation, in achieving a carbon neutral Wokingham Borough by 2030. Subsequently, in January 2020, the council published its first Climate Emergency Action Plan (CEAP), establishing the key priority areas to focus on for reducing CO2, all of which influence the long-term planning of the councils actions and direction. The action plan specifically focuses the councils current and future efforts on tackling emissions from transport, energy usage, generating renewable energy, planting more trees and other green foliage, encourage more recycling and encouraging behavioural change. This includes local planning, with targets focused around a local plan update, which seeks to incorporate sustainability measures and utilising renewable energy wherever possible, combined with support for active and sustainable travel infrastructure and green spaces. This is a live report which is continually reviewed and an updated progress report is published each year, documenting the progress on actions and changes within, which determines the long-term plan for many key areas of the council.",
      "financialPlanningImpact": "In order to prepare for potential climate related risks and minimise our own emissions to reduce the chances of such, significant resources have needed to be utilised in order to help achieve the targets set out in the action plan. Any projects relating to such are therefore incorporated into financial planning and require proposals in order to be approved and access the required resources. Where possible, funding for climate related actions is provided internally from council resources. However, due to the significant costs associated with the scale of this challenge, many of the actions are reliant on government funding in the form of grants or loans in order to be implemented, with payback from the savings in energy etc incorporated into the proposals for these cases.",
      "transitionRisks": "Reaching net-zero will create jobs and trade, but that transition to a green economy requires a workforce with the right skills and the risk is there will not be sufficient capacity to support such, along with insufficient funding from wider sources in order to fully implement measures needed to reach the low carbon economy. It is also vital to ensure that key services, energy etc are still delivered and there is the potential risk of these being affected if not considered and incorporated into climate action planning properly."
    },
